item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Our website address is: http:.

What personal data we collect and why we collect it

Comments

When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Contact forms

Cookies

If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Analytics

Who we share your data with

How long we retain your data

If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where we send your data

Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

Your contact information

Additional information

How we protect your data

What data breach procedures we have in place

What third parties we receive data from

What automated decision making and/or profiling we do with user data

Industry regulatory disclosure requirements

Corona beer still sees a profit despite being linked to virus

It is reported that Corona beer has not seen a decrease in sales despite being linked to the Coronavirus outbreak. It is said that sales this year has went up and does not have much exposure to international markets such as China.

BubbleTea

KFC dragonfruit burger

KFC releases dragonfruit burger with a pink bun in Vietnam after having excess fruit because of the coronavirus outbreak. It will be served for a limited time on March 20th.

Ramdon from the movie Parasite

Right from the popularity of Parasite, fans have been trying to make their own version of Ramdon. It is made with yummy chewy noodles, in Jjajang sauce in which it has a hint of spicy udon flavor. This noodle typically has steak and green onions cooked on top.

item.title: Popular Culture
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded:
Disney's Mulan will be delaying its release to a later date amid coronavirus concerns

As the highly anticipated movie was expected to release on March 26th, due to the coronavirus outbreak it is reported that Disney will delay the release of the movie to help prevent the spread. Other movies such as The New Mutants and Antlers will be postponed as well.

Parasite wins big as it is the first asian film to take home 4 major Academy Awards

It is named UK's most successful international film, as it took home best director, best picture, best international film and best original screenplay. This movie portrays two different families in Seoul one family that is living in poverty in a semi-basement while the other is wealthy in a great area and a large house.

Always be my maybe, a Netflix original starring Randal Park and Ali Wong

It is a romcom movie of two childhood sweethearts that had a fallen out and has not seen each for 15 years. Now living in two very different lives they reconnected in San Francisco and old sparks are still in the air.

Yappie: a comedy about the diversity among Asians

Directed and produced by Wong fu productions, it is a single camera comedy that dives into the social and racial issues related to Asian Americans through the experience of Andrew and his friends. For the first time, Andrew is questioning the invisibility of diversity that is around him and he wants to do something about it.

“If I could take a moment here in all honesty, I said ‘Yes’ to the fear of being on this stage tonight because I wanted to be here to look out into this audience and witness this moment of change,” Oh said. “And I’m not fooling myself. I’m not fooling myself. Next year could be different. It probably will be. But right now, this moment is real. Trust me, it is real. Because I see you. And I see you, all these faces of change, and now, so will everyone else.”

- Sandra Oh

“This is a great time, let’s keep this going and motivate each other so we can have more short films, feature films, series, and books coming from our community ... so we can have success stories,” 

- Philip Wang(Wong fu productions)

item.title: Videos
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded:
Kinjaz ft Ryan Higa: Take a break before you break

This video consist of two influential asians of Kinjaz and Ryan Higa. Kinjaz has revolutionized the dancing game in the dancing world. They have many accolades and is one of the most popular groups right now. Ryan Higa is a Youtuber and in the early 2010s he was highly regarded as the top YouTuber.

Wong Fu Productions: How are we still here??

As a Wongfu production video, this video shows what WongFu means to the Asian American community and how much they influence our generation and the new generation.

Wong Fu productions: Asian Bachelorette

If you have ever watched the Bachelor, there have been next to none Asians in the show. Wong Fu Productions was influenced by the idea and created a short that brings together some of the most popular online asian influencers in the society today.

Domics: Growing up asian

Domics is known for his animation videos, in this video he is talking about how it was to grow up as an asian in a Canada.

ABC News: Asians facing discrimination, violence amid Coronavirus outbreak

As the Coronavirus outbreak continues to spread, we are starting to see more and more discrimination and violence towards Asians as you can see in this video.

item.title: Racism continues as two possible hate crimes in NYC
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded: Hate crimes task force is investigating two cases in NYC as a 23 year old woman and a 59 year old man was attacked. The first case was a 23 year old woman was a student at the Zoni Language School in Midtown Manhattan when she was punched by another student say "Where's your corona mask, you Asian--". The 59 year old man was approached by a suspect and was stating anti-Asian statements.

item.title: 2020 Tokyo Olympics is still happening
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded: With the Olympics set to start on July 24th, the IOC is still set on continuing with the Olympics. The committee has until May to make the decision if they want to cancel or postpone the Olympics. It is estimated that 33 million visitors were set to visit Tokyo in 2020. There is speculation that because the NCAA tournament has been cancelled that instead of using NBA players they should use top college players to play in the Olympics.

item.title: Apple stores plan to close to help stop the Coronavirus retail stores outside China from spreading
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded: The Iphone maker is planning on closing its retail stores until further notice to stop the spreading of Coronavirus. They have announced that they will extend its in-store returns and repair programs until they reopen their stores.

item.title: BTS scores the second best selling song in the US with 'Sweet Night'
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded: BTS one of the best selling Korean boybands has just scored the second best selling song in the US with 'Sweet Night'. V from BTS has accumulated over 18M views and has debuted in the top 50 on the global youtube music video charts.

item.title: Blame game continues to escalate between US and China of coronavirus origins
item.dc:creator: jhum9
item.content:encoded: There has been tension brewing the US and china on who is to blame for the outbreak of the Coronavirus. United States president Trump who named it the 'chinese virus' has caused chinese president Xi Jinping to not hesitate in firing back. They suggested that the virus actually started in the US dating back to September 2019 and was misdiagnosed at that time. Trump has stated that China has allegedly tried to 'coverup' the information and the false claims from Chinese officials.
